{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:58","names":{"en":"Keita","tr":"Mali Keita Kralları","ar":"Mulūk Mālī min Āl Kayāta"},"country":["IR","ML","NE"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1230,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"58","atlas_name_en_original":"The Keita Kings of Mali","parent_tribe":"Keita boyu (Malinke/Mandinka)","ethnic_origin":"Malinke (Mandinka / Siyah Afrika)","capital":"Nyane (Sankarani üzerinde, değişen)","region_primary":"Batı Mali; Kuzey Gine; Gambiya; Senegal","regions_all":"Yukarı Nijer; Batı Mali; Kuzey Gine; Gambiya; Senegal; Timbuktu (geçici)","geographic_zone":"Doğu/Batı Afrika","predecessor":"Gana Krallığı (Soninke); Soso Krallığı","successor":"Songay İmparatorluğu; Bambara devletleri (Segu/Karta)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Keita Kings of Mali built West Africa's largest medieval empire, known to the world through Mansa Musa's legendary pilgrimage. They transformed Timbuktu into one of the Islamic world's important centers of learning; control of trans-Saharan gold trade brought immense wealth.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"11.4","capital_lon":"-8.7","century_start":null,"century_end":null}}
{"id":"Q663780","names":{"en":"Saadi Sultanate","tr":"Sa'dî Şerifler","ar":"al-Sa'diyyūn"},"country":["MA","NE","SD"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1510,"extinct":1659},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"20","atlas_name_en_original":"The Sa'did Sharifs","parent_tribe":"Hasanî Şerifler (Hz. Hasan soyundan)","ethnic_origin":"Arap (Şerif)","capital":"Merakeş (Marrākush); Fez (Fās)","region_primary":"Fas","regions_all":"Fas; Sûs; Nijer vadisi; Batı Afrika (Sudan)","geographic_zone":"Kuzey Afrika","predecessor":"Vattâsîler","successor":"Alevî/Filâlî Şerifler","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Sa'dian Sharifs rose under the banner of jihad against Portuguese occupation, becoming the first dynasty to rule Morocco through sharifian legitimacy. Ahmad al-Mansur's Sudan expedition destroyed the Songhai Empire and brought trans-Saharan gold trade under direct control; his epithet 'the Golden' derived from this wealth.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"31.63","capital_lon":"-8.01","century_start":16,"century_end":17}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:59","names":{"en":"Kings of Songhay","tr":"Songay Kralları","ar":"Mulūk Sunghāy"},"country":["ML","NE"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":1592},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"59","atlas_name_en_original":"The Kings of Songhay","parent_tribe":"Songay halkı (çeşitli kökenli)","ethnic_origin":"Songay / Soninke (Askiya kolunda)","capital":"Gao (Kawkaw)","region_primary":"Nijer bükümü boyunca savan bölgesi","regions_all":"Gao (Kawkaw); Timbuktu; Cenne (Jenne); Senegal'e kadar batı; Hausaland'a kadar doğu","geographic_zone":"Doğu/Batı Afrika","predecessor":"Mali İmparatorluğu (hakimiyet)","successor":"Fas paşaları (Timbuktu); bölgesel parçalanma","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Songhai Kings inherited the Mali Empire's legacy and built West Africa's most territorially extensive state. Askia Muhammad's Mecca pilgrimage and Islamic reform program integrated the empire with the Islamic world. The expedition by Moroccan Sa'did sultan Ahmad al-Mansur's army equipped with firearms destroyed this vast empire.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"16.27","capital_lon":"-0.04","century_start":null,"century_end":null}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:61","names":{"en":"Fulani Rulers in Hausaland, as Sultans and","tr":"Hausaland Fulani Hükümdarları (Sokoto Sultanları/Halifeleri)","ar":"Umarā' al-Fulānī fī Bilād Hawsā / Salāṭīn Sukūtū"},"country":["ML","NE","NG"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1804,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"61","atlas_name_en_original":"The Fulani Rulers in Hausaland, as Sultans and Caliphs of Sokoto","parent_tribe":"Fulani (Fulbe) / Tokolor","ethnic_origin":"Fulani (Fulbe)","capital":"Sokoto (Sakwato, 1224/1809 kuruldu); Gwandu (batı)","region_primary":"Kuzey Nijerya (Hausaland)","regions_all":"Sokoto; Gwandu; Hausaland (Kano, Katsina, Zaria vb.); Adamawa (Kuzey Kamerun)","geographic_zone":"Doğu/Batı Afrika","predecessor":"Hausa emirlikleri","successor":"(İngiliz sömürge yönetimi; dolaylı yönetim ile devam; Nijerya Cumhuriyeti içinde)","government_type":"Sultanlık|Emirlik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Sokoto Caliphate was a Fulani dynasty founded through Uthman dan Fodio's jihad movement, unifying the Hausa emirates of northern Nigeria. Shaped by the influence of Sufi orders, this movement represents the most comprehensive political expression of Islamic reformism in sub-Saharan Africa.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"13.06","capital_lon":"5.24","century_start":null,"century_end":null}}
